Self-antigen presentation and central tolerance: During thymic development, self-antigens presented by HLA molecules on thymic antigen-presenting cells drive negative selection (clonal deletion) of autoreactive T cells. If an HLA variant dramatically increases presentation of a self-antigen, it would lead to more efficient negative selection of T cells reactive to that antigen → fewer autoreactive T cells in the periphery. 2. Peripheral tolerance: More efficient presentation of self-antigens can also promote peripheral tolerance mechanisms (Treg induction, anergy). 3. Autoimmune disease logic: Many HLA alleles associated with increased autoimmune disease risk are often those that present self-antigens poorly or present them in altered conformations, allowing autoreactive T cells to escape deletion. Conversely, certain HLA alleles protect against autoimmunity by efficiently presenting self-antigens
